	  </exercise>
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>By trial and error find at least one solution of the given equation. – You do not need to find all solutions.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>3x + y = 5</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Try substituting an arbitrary number for one of the variables. Then solve for the other.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Often one can find particular solutions of a given equation by substituting random values for all but one of the variables in the equation. What remains is an equation in one variable only, and this equation can often be solved. For example, in the case at hand:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <ul>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>(0,5)</latex>
                              </math> is a solution of the given equation, found by substituting <math>
                                 <latex>0</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>x</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>(1,2)</latex>
                              </math> is a solution of the given equation, found by substituting <math>
                                 <latex>1</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>x</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>(4,-7)</latex>
                              </math> is a solution of the given equation, found by substituting <math>
                                 <latex>4</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>x</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>(5/3,0)</latex>
                              </math> is a solution of the given equation, found by substituting <math>
                                 <latex>0</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>y</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
					             </ul>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>2x - y + 3z = 0</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Try substituting <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math> for <math>
                        <latex>x</latex>
                     </math> and for <math>
                        <latex>y</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>There are many correct answers; for example:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <ul>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>(1,1,-1/3)</latex>
                              </math> is a solution of the given equation, found by substituting <math>
                                 <latex>1</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>x</latex>
                              </math>, and <math>
                                 <latex>1</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>y</latex>
                              </math>
                           </para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>(1,5,1)</latex>
                              </math>  is a solution of the given equation, found by substituting <math>
                                 <latex>1</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>x</latex>
                              </math>, and <math>
                                 <latex>1</latex>
                              </math> for <math>
                                 <latex>z</latex>
                              </math>
                           </para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
					             </ul>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>x^2 + y^2 = 1</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 4</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>w^2 + x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 9</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>x^4 + y^4 + z^4 = -1</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This equation has no solution <math>
                           <latex>(x,y,z)</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math> because</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <ol>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>x^4,y^4,z^4 \geq 0</latex>
                              </math> for all <math>
                                 <latex>x,y,z</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr</latex>
                              </math>. So, for all possible substitutions of real number values for <math>
                                 <latex>x,y,z</latex>
                              </math>, the statement <math>
                                 <latex>x^4 + y^4 + z^4 = -1</latex>
                              </math> is false.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
					             </ol>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <caption>Simultaneous equations</caption>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Determine if the given point is a simultaneous solution of the two given equations; i.e. if it turns both equations into a true statement.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(1,1)</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>x-y^2 = 0</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>x^2 - y = 0</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>(1,1)</latex>
                        </math> is a simultaneous solution of the given equations because both of the resulting statements</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>1 - 1^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>0</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>1^2 - 1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>0</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>are true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(1,4,1)</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>2x + y - 3z = 1</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>x + y - 5z = 0</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>(1,4,1)</latex>
                        </math> is not a simultaneous solution of <math>
                           <latex>2x + y - 3z = 1</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>x + y - 5z = 0</latex>
                        </math> because one of the resulting statements</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>2\cdot 1 + 4 -3\cdot 1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>1\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 4 - 5\cdot 1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>0</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>is not true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(2,2,2)</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>x+y+z=6</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 6</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>(2,2,2)</latex>
                           </math> is not a simultaneous solution of the two given equations.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
